WEBVTT

00:02.553 --> 00:06.896
I've always wondered why baseball
is so associated with sex.

00:07.073 --> 00:10.509
"He's playing the field. He scored.
He didn't get to first base."

00:10.677 --> 00:12.440
"I struck out." "Why?"
"She wanted a diamond."

00:12.612 --> 00:16.548
It's always baseball,
always baseball.

00:16.716 --> 00:20.345
As far as baseball goes,
I prefer the fat umpires.

00:20.520 --> 00:22.579
If you're on the field
and not in the game...

00:22.756 --> 00:26.385
...you should be in the worst physical
condition a human could be in.

00:26.559 --> 00:29.960
They should be allowed
to eat during the game.

00:30.997 --> 00:34.091
We're too into sports in this country.
We gotta throttle back.

00:34.267 --> 00:35.962
People come home
from these games:

00:36.136 --> 00:39.663
"We won, we won!"
No, they won, you watched.

00:44.911 --> 00:49.348
Okay, Danny. Take a swing.
No, no, no.

00:49.516 --> 00:51.814
-You're opening up your shoulder.
-Really?

00:51.985 --> 00:56.012
No, not really. I'm just saying this to
you because I like to hear myself talk.

00:56.189 --> 00:57.781
Yes, really.

00:57.957 --> 00:59.618
All right, all right.

00:59.793 --> 01:02.728
-What are you all sweating for?
-It's hot in this uniform.

01:03.229 --> 01:06.960
-Hot? What is this?
-What is what?

01:07.133 --> 01:09.033
This uniform. What's it made from?

01:09.202 --> 01:11.227
-I don't know. Cotton?
-No. No, no.

01:11.404 --> 01:13.099
This is not cotton. Here, let me see.

01:13.273 --> 01:15.298
-What are you doing?
-I wanna see the label.

01:15.475 --> 01:17.500
Will you stop it? Come on.

01:18.578 --> 01:22.241
-Oh, of course. Polyester!
-So?

01:22.415 --> 01:25.350
-I can't believe you're not in cotton.
-This is what they give us.

01:25.518 --> 01:28.351
You know they used to make
leisure suits out of this fabric?

01:28.521 --> 01:30.921
-You really think cotton is better?
-Of course.

01:31.091 --> 01:33.184
All right, maybe I'll say
something to Buck.

01:34.127 --> 01:36.960
-Yeah, good idea. Catch you later.
-Yeah.

01:37.130 --> 01:38.722
Hey, don't embarrass me today.

01:38.898 --> 01:41.332
I got some friends in the stands.

01:46.739 --> 01:49.333
-Hot dogs here. Yankee franks.
-Oh, you want one?

01:49.509 --> 01:50.737
-Yeah.
-I'll get it.

01:50.910 --> 01:52.207
-I got it.
-Jerry.

01:52.378 --> 01:54.744
-Elaine, stop it.
-Just because I'm not working...

01:54.914 --> 01:57.781
...doesn't mean I don't have
any money. Yo. Dogs. Two.

01:57.951 --> 01:59.543
All right. I'm sorry.

01:59.719 --> 02:02.279
<i>Your attention, please.
The New York Yankees...</i>

02:02.455 --> 02:05.754
<i>...would like to welcome
Miss Connecticut...</i>

02:05.925 --> 02:09.691
<i>...Miss Rhode Island
and Miss North Dakota.</i>

02:09.863 --> 02:14.061
<i>All of whom will be competing
in the Miss America pageant...</i>

02:14.234 --> 02:18.398
<i>... this weekend in Atlantic City.</i>

02:18.571 --> 02:21.768
Now, there's a career path
you may have overlooked.

02:21.975 --> 02:25.035
Oh, I gotta check my machine. I'm
waiting to hear about an interview.

02:25.211 --> 02:29.409
Doubleday is looking for somebody
to replace Jackie Onassis.

02:29.582 --> 02:31.982
-She worked at Doubleday?
-Yeah, she was an editor.

02:32.152 --> 02:33.915
-Oh, right, just like you.
-Yeah.

02:34.087 --> 02:35.520
-Would you move your feet?
-Yeah.

02:35.688 --> 02:39.124
-Hey, lady!
-Hey, down in front!

02:39.292 --> 02:42.056
-Hey!
-Move your feet.

02:42.629 --> 02:45.359
-I'm going.
-Come on.

02:47.734 --> 02:49.929
-Hot dog?
-No, thanks.

02:50.103 --> 02:53.334
-I'm watching my weight.
-I'm watching my height.

02:53.506 --> 02:56.202
My doctor doesn't want me
to get any taller.

02:57.677 --> 03:00.669
-So you're Miss...?
-Rhode Island.

03:00.847 --> 03:04.715
I was almost Mr. Coffee.
They felt I was a little too relaxed.

03:07.120 --> 03:08.348
Miss Rhode Island?

03:09.022 --> 03:11.456
-When are you seeing her?
-Tonight. I have to call her.

03:11.624 --> 03:13.182
She's staying in a hotel.

03:13.359 --> 03:15.259
-You're incredible.
-And get this:

03:15.428 --> 03:17.362
I'm working Atlantic City
this weekend.

03:17.530 --> 03:19.361
She's gonna be there
for the pageant.

03:19.532 --> 03:23.866
What if she becomes Miss America?
You could be dating Miss America.

03:24.037 --> 03:26.562
The only bad thing is we have
to go out with a chaperone.

03:26.739 --> 03:28.730
Chaperone? What, are you kidding?

03:28.908 --> 03:31.570
-No. It's the contest rules.
-What does the chaperone do?

03:31.744 --> 03:34.212
I don't know. She just sits there.

03:35.515 --> 03:39.542
-Can she talk?
-I'm not sure if she's allowed to talk.

03:40.153 --> 03:42.348
-Are you calling her?
-Yeah.

03:46.392 --> 03:49.088
Yes. Room 417, please.
Karen Hanson.

03:49.262 --> 03:52.493
Hey, did you know the Yankees
don't wear cotton jerseys?

03:52.665 --> 03:54.257
Of course. They're polyester.

03:54.434 --> 03:57.232
Well, what is that? That's a crime.

03:57.403 --> 04:00.395
You know how hot those things get?
They should be wearing cotton.

04:00.573 --> 04:02.905
-Why do they wear polyester?
-I don't know.

04:03.076 --> 04:04.600
That's all gonna change.

04:06.379 --> 04:09.109
-You're gonna do something about it?
-Why shouldn't l?

04:10.550 --> 04:12.415
No reason.

04:15.989 --> 04:19.481
Of course, Jackie O
was a great lady.

04:19.659 --> 04:22.719
Those are gonna be
some tough shoes to fill.

04:22.895 --> 04:25.193
Everyone loved her.

04:25.365 --> 04:27.060
She had such...

04:27.233 --> 04:30.100
-...grace.
-Yes!

04:32.105 --> 04:35.165
-Grace!
-Not many people have grace.

04:36.042 --> 04:38.636
Well, you know,
grace is a tough one.

04:38.811 --> 04:40.904
I like to think I have a little grace.

04:41.080 --> 04:44.311
-Not as much as Jackie O, but--
-You can't have a little grace.

04:44.484 --> 04:48.545
You either have grace
or you don't.

04:50.256 --> 04:53.623
Okay, fine. I have no grace.

04:54.861 --> 04:57.056
And you can't acquire grace.

04:57.230 --> 05:00.688
Well, I have no intention
of getting grace.

05:00.867 --> 05:04.132
Grace isn't something
you can pick up at the market.

05:04.304 --> 05:08.331
All right, look. I don't have grace,
I don't want grace...

05:08.508 --> 05:11.068
...I don't even say grace, okay?

05:13.913 --> 05:16.677
-Thank you for coming in.
-Yeah, yeah, right.

05:18.551 --> 05:22.681
We'll make our choice in a few days
and we'll let you know.

05:22.855 --> 05:25.722
-I have no chance, do l?
-No.

05:25.892 --> 05:27.621
All right. Thanks.

05:27.794 --> 05:29.625
Justin Pitt to see you.

05:29.796 --> 05:32.822
-Justin Pitt?
-He was a very close friend...

05:32.999 --> 05:34.261
...of Mrs. Onassis'.

05:34.434 --> 05:37.267
Mrs. Onassis'.
That's hard to pronounce.

05:37.437 --> 05:40.201
-Excuse me?
-Nothing, nothing.

05:40.373 --> 05:43.274
Mrs. Landis, there's something
wrong with this copying machine.

05:43.443 --> 05:45.070
